[
    {
        "content": "<p>There is a free group monad, and an algebra of the free group monad is a group. A group G defines a monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi>G</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\mapsto G \\times A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. An algebra of this monad is a G-set, or a group equipped with a G-action.</p>\n<p>Similarly we have that rings are algebras of a certain monad on Abelian groups ( the free tensor algebra monad) and a ring R itself also defines a monad on Abelian groups whose algebras are the R-modules.</p>\n<p>I am interested in the general theory of these structures where one has an algebraic class of structures which can have their own modules/algebras. What is this situation called? Where can I read about it?</p>",
        "id": 311200342,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1668991613
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that there's a \"universal\" case: there is a <a href=\"https://www.maths.usyd.edu.au/u/ResearchReports/Catecomb/Lack/1997-29.html\">free monad monad</a>, whose algebras are (finitary) monads, which of course have their own algebras.</p>",
        "id": 311216052,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1669006821
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you for the paper reference.</p>",
        "id": 311407243,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1669044500
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In general, <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/monoid+in+a+monoidal+category\">monoid objects in monoidal categories</a> are the kind of thing that that have 'modules' or 'algebras', also called 'actions'.  </p>\n<p>A monad on a category C is a monoid in the monoidal category of endofunctors on C.  A ring is a monoid in the monoidal category of abelian groups.  An operad is a monoid in a the monoidal category of species.   Etcetera.</p>",
        "id": 311465848,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1669061156
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So I guess one general context would be when you have a monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> on a monoidal category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and a map of monads <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{fm} \\to T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">fm</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{fm}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">fm</span></span></span></span></span> is the free monoid monad on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.  Then any <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span>-algebra has an underlying monoid, which therefore acts on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and induces a new monad.</p>",
        "id": 311478002,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1669066118
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So for instance <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> might be the free group monad on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\rm Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, for your first example.</p>",
        "id": 311478084,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1669066177
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's also a general notion of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/module%20over%20an%20algebra%20over%20an%20operad\">[[module over an algebra over an operad]]</a>. I don't know how this works in detail and there isn't much on the nLab page either, but presumably the paper linked there contains more details.</p>",
        "id": 311479171,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Fritz",
        "timestamp": 1669066654
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0305049.pdf#page=152\">Example 4.3.14 in Tom Leinster's \"Higher Operads, Higher Categories\"</a> references that slices of the category of algebras of a monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span> are monadic over the corresponding slices of the underlying category, so if you allow the monad to be on a different-but-related category this happens for <em>any</em> monad.</p>\n<p>As far as the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/module%20over%20an%20algebra%20over%20an%20operad\">[[module over an algebra over an operad]]</a> idea goes, it seems like you could generalize it to algebras of any <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/polynomial%20monad\">[[polynomial monad]]</a> where the base category allows a good notion of total differential of polynomial functors.</p>",
        "id": 326703812,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1675898123
    }
]